                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.9412Anti-War/93: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Neville</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-09T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 9, 1929—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>14. Trying to get the Japanese to act on the ratification of the Paris peace pact
                    has rather discouraged me, and I am not able to get any assurance from them that
                    they intend to act at any time within the near future. If Japan could ratify
                    before I leave office about March 25 or 26, I would accept a telegraphic copy of
                    their ratification and later substitute their original.</p>
                <p>On March 7 I intimated to the Japanese Ambassador that, should Japan not intend
                    to ratify the pact within the near future, I might be forced to request the
                    other Powers to sign a protocol putting the treaty into effect without Japanese
                    ratification.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
